{"id":"1910.04521","submitter":"Michele Castellana","authors":"Michele Castellana","title":"Real-space renormalization-group methods for hierarchical spin glasses","comments":null,"journal-ref":"Journal of Physics A: Mathematical and Theoretical 52(44), 445002\n  (2019)","doi":"10.1088/1751-8121/ab2f46","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.dis-nn cond-mat.stat-mech","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We focus on two real-space renormalization-group (RG) methods recently\nproposed for a hierarchical model of a spin glass: A sample-by-sample method,\nin which the RG transformation is performed separately on each disorder sample,\nand an ensemble RG (ERG) method [M. C. Angelini, G. Parisi, and F.\nRicci-Tersenghi. Ensemble renormalization group for disordered systems.\n$\\textit{Phys. Rev. B}$, 87(13):134201, 2013] in which the transformation is\nbased on an average over samples. Above the upper critical dimension, the\nsample-by-sample method yields the correct mean-field value for the critical\nexponent $\\nu$ related to the divergence of the correlation length, while it\ndoes not predict the correct qualitative behavior of $\\nu$ below the upper\ncritical dimension. On the other hand, the ERG procedure has been claimed to\npredict the correct behavior of $\\nu$ both above and below the upper critical\ndimension. Here, we straighten out the reasons for the discrepancy between the\ntwo methods above, by demonstrating that the ERG method predicts a marginally\nstable critical fixed point, thus implying a prediction for the critical\nexponent $\\nu$ given by $2^{1/\\nu} = 1$. This prediction disagrees, on a\nqualitative and quantitative level, both with the mean-field value of $\\nu$\nabove the critical dimension, and with numerical estimates of $\\nu$ below the\nupper critical dimension. Therefore, our results show that finding a real-space\nRG method for spin glasses which yields the correct prediction for universal\nquantities below the upper critical dimension is still an open problem, for\nwhich our analysis may provide some general guidance for future studies.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 10 Oct 2019 12:45:59 GMT"}],"update_date":"2019-10-11"}
